<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/15/at-salt-conference-stocks-induce-anxiety/" data-title="At SALT Conference, Stocks Induce Anxiety" data-description="At the hedge fund industry&#039;s annual gathering in Las Vegas, managers voiced concerns about the direction of the stock market.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">LAS VEGAS &#8212; At the the <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/05/08/hedge-fund-impresario-plays-host-in-las-vegas/" title="Hedge Fund Impresario Plays Host in Las Vegas">SkyBridge Alternatives Conference</a> here, <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/14/what-hedge-funds-talk-about-when-they-talk-about-money/" title="What Hedge Funds Talk About When They Talk About Money">hedge fund managers are gathering</a> at the Bellagio hotel to exchange views and ideas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whether it is in the marbled hallways of the hotel, or the giant ballroom where the conference panels are taking place, one question prevails: Is it time to be worried about the United States stock market?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For the hedge fund titan David Tepper, itâs ânervous time.â</p>
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Tepper &#8212; who founded the $20 billion hedge fund Appaloosa Management &#8212; sounded a warning note on Wednesday afternoon to a room packed with hedge fund managers, wealth advisers and investors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;I&#8217;m not saying go short, just don&#8217;t be too friggin&#8217; long,&#8221; he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was an unusual statement from a manager who built his hedge fund by making bold and bullish bets on down-and-out stocks like airlines, auto and financial stocks in 2013 and financial firms in 2009.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Mr. Tepper is concerned about the country&#8217;s economic growth, which he said had been slower than he expected this year. He advised his audience to hold onto some cash.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âListen, there are times to make money and there are times not to lose money,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Standard &#038; Poorâs 500 stock-index has reached a record recently, but some high-growth sectors like technology have experienced broad sell-offs, something that has burned many hedge funds managers who bought heavily into stocks like Google and Tesla. Some managers here are asking whether the sell-off could bleed into other sectors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">More broadly, investors have voiced concern about the consequences of an abrupt end to the Federal Reserveâs quantitative easing program, which has helped to push asset prices higher by pumping money into the system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThere seems to be a general unease that with central bank policy, the only thing it is impacting are financial markets,&#8221; said Jim Chanos, president of Kynikos Associates and a well-known short-seller. &#8220;Itâs not transmitting to the economy, and I think that is a real, real growing concern.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âYou sort of get a growing sense that this grand experiment may be quite inconclusive when it comes to monetary policy and financial markets,â Mr. Chanos added, speaking on the sidelines of the conference on Thursday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At a lunch with private wealth managers and hedge fund managers before SALT kicked off on Tuesday, one trader voiced his own concerns about the Fedâs policy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIâm just trying to understand this gigantic world experiment,â Lawrence Altman of CBD Trading said. He asked whether the consequences of high asset prices and little real economic growth scared anyone else in the room.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday, David M. Rubenstein, the co-chief executive of the Carlyle Group, warned of âfrothinessâ in the market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe markets are not cheap.â Mr. Rubenstein said, adding that âin the buyout world itâs actually difficult to find deals.â </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/15/business/dealbook/dbpix-salt/dbpix-salt-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/15/business/dealbook/dbpix-salt/dbpix-salt-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/15/business/dealbook/dbpix-salt/dbpix-salt-blog480.jpg" id="100000002883681" width="480" height="320" alt="David M. Rubenstein, the co-chief executive of the Carlyle Group, warned of âfrothinessâ in the stock market."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">David M. Rubenstein, the co-chief executive of the Carlyle Group, warned of âfrothinessâ in the stock market.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Rick Wilking/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But not everyone who gathered at what Wall Street calls the Super Bowl of hedge funds agrees.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Leon G. Cooperman, the head of Omega Advisors, boldly predicted that the S.&#038;P. 500 could close this year around 2,000 points, a sharp climb from its close of 1,870.85 on Thursday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Cooperman said he did not think the conditions that go with a bear market were visible today.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But, he added, âOverall Iâm positive with a small &#8216;p.&#8217;â</p>
	</div>
